Mark`s Notes
AI analyzes genetic and medical data to find disease-causing patterns. Uses large databases such as Drugbank and PubChem.
It helps identify targets for diseases such as Alzheimer's disease, Cancer, and Parkinson's disease
AI can analyze millions of molecules quickly.
It predicts how molecules will interact with disease targets.
This reduces the time needed for laboratory experiments.
During the COVID-19 pandemic, AI helped researchers screen potential antiviral drugs much faster than traditional methods.
AI analyzes genomics data to identify disease-related genes and proteins.
A genome is the complete set of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) within an organism.
Machine learning models identify gene–disease relationships and biomarkers.
Biomarkers (short for biological markers) are objective, measurable indicators of a biological state or condition.
Deep learning models can analyze complex biological datasets to predict disease outcomes.
AI identifies drug toxicity and adverse reactions early.
Optimizes clinical trial design, patient recruitment, and data analysis.
Enables real-time monitoring of trial data.
AI models generate new drug molecules.
AI finds new uses for existing drugs.
Main Issues:
Lack of high-quality training data.
Data from multiple sources can be difficult to integrate.
Hard for researchers to interpret how decisions are made.
Data privacy, legal challenges and job displacement. 
